        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faq" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on Kennismigrant visa?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Yes, but the new employer must also be a recognized IND sponsor and you must still meet salary thresholds. Notify IND of the change. If you're between jobs, you have 3 months to find new qualifying employment before your permit is at risk.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens to 30% ruling if I change jobs?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">The 30% ruling can transfer to a new employer within 3 months of leaving your previous job. The new role must still meet the specific expertise requirement and minimum salary. You don't restart the 5-year clock—it continues from the original grant date.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is family covered under my health insurance?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">No, each adult needs their own basisverzekering. Children under 18 are free and covered under a parent's policy. Spouse/partner must purchase their own insurance, but the combined household may qualify for higher zorgtoeslag (subsidy).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I use international insurance instead of Dutch?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">No, if you're a Dutch resident (registered at gemeente), you must have Dutch basisverzekering by law. You can add international coverage on top for global travel or enhanced benefits, but it doesn't replace the mandatory Dutch insurance.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get permanent residence?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">After 5 years of continuous legal residence, you can apply for permanent residence (onbepaalde tijd). You must pass the civic integration exam (inburgeringsexamen) including Dutch language test. Alternative: EU long-term residence after 5 years.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if my salary drops below the threshold?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">If your salary falls below Kennismigrant thresholds (e.g., reduced hours, demotion), your permit may be at risk. The IND doesn't actively monitor, but issues arise at renewal. Temporary drops during parental leave are usually acceptable with documentation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        The Netherlands offers one of Europe's smoothest paths for skilled workers. The Kennismigrant scheme, combined with the 30% ruling, creates a genuinely attractive package for international talent. Processing is fast (often 2-3 weeks), English proficiency is near-universal, and the quality of life is high.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        The Dutch health insurance system requires adjustment but works well once understood. The GP gatekeeper model and eigen risico (deductible) may frustrate those used to direct specialist access, but costs are reasonable and care quality is excellent. Add dental coverage—it's worth the €15-20/month.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        The major challenge is housing. Budget significantly more than you expect, start searching before arrival, and be prepared for temporary housing initially. The 30% ruling's tax savings often offset higher rents, but the stress of finding accommodation is real.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-2">Bottom Line</h3>
        <p class="text-primary-800">The Netherlands is ideal for English-speaking professionals wanting European lifestyle with strong career opportunities. The Kennismigrant + 30% ruling combination is hard to beat for take-home pay. Dutch health insurance is mandatory and affordable—just remember to get dental add-on coverage. The only real obstacles are the housing crisis and finding a GP with capacity.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

